opia has now been forgotten. The book takes a distinctive approach to exploring the value to society of social town planning and offers a doorway for how planning, both morally and practically, can help to meet key challenges of the 21st century. It challenges the widely held view that it’s impossible to achieve a better future by suggesting that there is real choice in how society develops and pointing to contemporary examples of utopia. This accessible book makes essential reading for students in the built environment and the wider social sciences who have an interest in UK and European examples of sustainable communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCity planningzGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aHenderson, Kate, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHetherington, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311119634340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447317623423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447317623/original  a978-3-11-119634-3  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles